# Stitches Rules

This project uses Codestitch — pre-built HTML/CSS sections dropped into Eleventy templates. All section HTML and CSS uses the `cs-` class prefix (short for CodeStitch).

## Adding a new stitch

### 1. Create the section file

Save the stitch HTML as a `.html` file in the appropriate folder:

- `src/_includes/sections/home/` — sections used only on the home page
- `src/_includes/sections/` — sections used across multiple pages (e.g. cta, header, footer)

Example: `src/_includes/sections/home/pricing.html`

### 2. Add the SCSS

Paste the stitch's CSS into the relevant file in `src/assets/sass/`:

- `local.scss` — page-specific styles, loaded after render
- `critical.scss` — above-the-fold styles that must load immediately

### 3. Include it in the page

Add a `{% include %}` tag in the page file where you want the section to appear. The order of includes controls the order sections appear on the page.

```html
{% block body %}
    {% include "sections/home/hero.html" %}
    {% include "sections/home/pricing.html" %}
    {% include "sections/cta.html" %}
{% endblock %}
```

## Key conventions

- All sections live in `src/_includes/` so Eleventy does not publish them as pages
- CSS class names always use the `cs-` prefix — do not rename them
- Never put raw `<style>` tags inside section HTML files — all styles go in the SASS files
- Images inside stitches must use the `{% getUrl %}` pipeline — see images.mdc
